## Migration Analysis

Your code has three .NET Framework APIs that **won't work in .NET 8**:

| API | Problem in .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `ProcessLoop` while-loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Exception as control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Stop()` abort after timeout | Timeout enforcement | `Thread.Join(timeout)` + `cts.Cancel()` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking call can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — mirrors the old ThreadAbortException block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control the loop via the token.
                // Loop condition will exit naturally on next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. With cooperative cancellation,
            // this means GetNextItem/ProcessItem isn't checking the token.
            // Log a warning — there is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in .NET 8.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept the token.** The original comment says "may block." If it blocks forever, cancellation never fires — cooperative cancellation only works if the code checks the token:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, can't be cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem() =>
    _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()

// AFTER — wakes up when token is cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token) =>
    _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
```

**2. `Thread.Sleep` in the loop?** If `ProcessItem` or any downstream code calls `Thread.Sleep`, replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so cancellation can interrupt the wait.

**3. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` silently.** The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures we only catch *our* cancellation, not someone else's. Other `OperationCanceledException`s propagate normally.

**4. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The `IDisposable` pattern on the class handles this.

**5. No forced termination exists.** If the thread truly can't cooperate (e.g., calling unmanaged code that blocks forever), the only .NET 8 option is moving that work to a **child process** and using `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`.
